h1. Notes on AutoScaling and ELB

h3. UPLOADING SSL CERTIFICATES FOR ELB
Thecommand to upload is {{euare-servercertupload}}
{code}
euare-servercertupload -s cert-name --certificate-file ssl_server_cert.crt --private-key-file ssl_server_cert.pem
{code}

to list certs:
{code}
$ euare-servercertlistbypath
arn:aws:iam::495375389014:server-certificate/elb-ssl-test-1400696779
arn:aws:iam::495375389014:server-certificate/elb-ssl-cert
arn:aws:iam::495375389014:server-certificate/elb-ssl-test-1400696266
arn:aws:iam::495375389014:server-certificate/euca-internal/euca-internal-imaging-service
{code}
or
{code}
$ euare-servercertgetattributes -s elb-ssl-cert
arn:aws:iam::495375389014:server-certificate/elb-ssl-cert
ASCWDKTJBXPSZTHWFERVP
{code}

h3. CREATING A BASIC AUTO SCALING CONFIGURATION:
{quote}
euscale-create-auto-scaling-group MyScalingGroup --launch-configuration MyLaunchConfig --availability-zones PARTI00 --min-size 2 --max-size 5
{quote}

This does not configure an auto scaling group to actually launch any instances which is shown in the output of the describe autoscaling group example.  
Suggest changing to:
{quote}
euscale-create-auto-scaling-group MyScalingGroup --launch-configuration MyLaunchConfig --availability-zones PARTI00 --min-size 2 --max-size 5 --desired-capacity 2
{quote}

[~smarvin], 

I created this to be added as an example under ['Eucalyptus Load Balancing Usage Examples'|https://www-stage.eucalyptus-systems.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.0/index.html#user-guide/elb_examples_intro.html]. 

*Steps to Create HTTPS/SSL ELB ( modified version of http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ElasticLoadBalancing/latest/DeveloperGuide/US_SettingUpLoadBalancerHTTPS.html )*

1)  Configure Listeners
* Create SSL Certificate for Load Balancer
** Create private key
{code}$ openssl genrsa 2048 > acmes-dev-euca.pem{code}
** If submitting the Certificate Signing Request to a Certificate Authority, generate CSR (http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ElasticLoadBalancing/latest/DeveloperGuide/ssl-server-cert.html).  If not, create a self-signed certificate.  (Note: for production use, we recommend generating a CSR.  Self-signed certificates are great for testing):
*** Generate a CSR
{code}$ openssl req -new -key acmes-dev-euca.pem -out acme-dev-csr.pem{code}
or
*** Generate a self-signed certificate
{code}$ openssl req -new -x509 -key acmes-dev-euca.pem -out acmes-cacert.pem -days 1095{code}
** Upload the Certificate
*** If not in PEM format, create PEM format private key 
{code}$ openssl rsa -in acmes-dev-euca.pem -outform PEM > acmes-dev-euca-pem.pem{code}
*** If not in PEM format, create PEM format public certificate
{code}$ openssl x509 -inform PEM -in acmes-cacert.pem > acmes-cacert-pem.pem{code}
*** \[\*\] (In case a certificate chain was provided by the CA) Typically, both intermediate and root certificates are provided by a CA in a bundled file with the proper chained order. If a certificate bundle is not available or not available in the required order, you can create your own certificate chain file.  To create your own certificate chain file, include the intermediate certificates and optionally, the root certificate, one after the other without any blank lines. If you are including the root certificate, your certificate chain must start with intermediate certificates and end with the root certificate. Use the intermediate certificates that were provided by your CA. Any intermediaries that are not involved in the chain of trust path must not be included. Once there is a certificate chain and its not in PEM format, create PEM format certificate chain
{code}$ openssl x509 -inform PEM -in acmes-cachain-cert.pem > acmes-cachain-cert-pem.pem{code}
*** Upload certificates
**** With no certificate chain
{code}$ euare-servercertupload -s acmes-dev-eucalyptus --certificate-file acmes-cacert-pem.pem --private-key-file acmes-dev-euca-pem.pem{code}
**** With certificate chain
{code}$ euare-servercertupload -s acmes-dev-eucalyptus --certificate-file acmes-cacert-pem.pem --private-key-file acmes-dev-euca-pem.pem --certificate-chain-file acmes-cachain-cert-pem.pem{code}
** Confirm certificate
{code}$ euare-servercertgetattributes -s acmes-dev-eucalyptus
arn:aws:iam::408396244283:server-certificate/acmes-dev-eucalyptus
ASCH4UCWZA6D6V0TLQQOG{code}

b) Create LB with Listeners
{code}$ eulb-create-lb MyLoadBalancer -z AcmeAvailabilityZone -l "lb-port=80, protocol=HTTP, instance-port=80, instance-protocol=HTTP" -l "lb-port=443, protocol=https, instance-port=80, instance-protocol=http, cert-id=arn:aws:iam::408396244283:server-certificate/acmes-dev-eucalyptus"{code}
\[\*\]  For more information regarding creating listeners, please refer to the following sections from this resource - http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ElasticLoadBalancing/latest/DeveloperGuide/elb-listener-config.html
* Listeners
* Using HTTP/HTTPS Protocol with Elastic Load Balancing
* Using Back-End Server Authentication with Elastic Load Balancing
	  
2) Configure Health Check
{code}$ eulb-configure-healthcheck MyLoadBalancer --target "HTTP:80/" --interval 30 --timeout 2 --unhealthy-threshold 2 --healthy-threshold 2{code}

3) Launch and register instances.  EMI used for instances can be either pre-baked with web server, or configured upon launching the instance using userdata file.
* Create security group for instances
{code}$ euca-create-group mysecuritygroup -d "Security Group for HTTPS/SSL Web Servers"{code}
* Authorize ELB security group for back-end port communication with instance security group
{code}
$ eulb-describe-lbs --show-long
LOAD_BALANCER	MyLoadBalancer	MyLoadBalancer-408396244283.elb.acme.eucalyptus-systems.com			{interval=30,target=HTTP:80/,timeout=2,healthy-threshold=2,unhealthy-threshold=2}	AcmeAvailabilityZone				{protocol=HTTP,lb-port=80,instance-protocol=HTTP,instance-port=80},{protocol=HTTPS,lb-port=443,instance-protocol=HTTP,instance-port=80,cert-id=arn:aws:iam::408396244283:server-certificate/acmes-dev-eucalyptus}					{owner-alias=944786667073,group-name=euca-internal-408396244283-MyLoadBalancer}		2014-05-29T02:14:00.141Z
$ euca-authorize mysecuritygroup -u 944786667073 -o euca-internal-408396244283-MyLoadBalancer -p -1
{code}
* Launch instances
{code}$ euca-run-instances -g mysecuritygroup -n 2 -t m1.medium emi-50783D25{code}
* Register instances with ELB
{code}$ eulb-register-instances-with-lb MyLoadBalancer --instances i-A564BC81,i-B17317D1{code}
4) Verify Details of Load Balancer
{code}
$ eulb-describe-instance-health MyLoadBalancer --show-long
	INSTANCE	i-B17317D1	InService
	INSTANCE	i-A564BC81	InService
{code}

Hey [~smarvin],

Here is another example that I think should be added to ['Auto Scaling Usage Examples'|https://www-stage.eucalyptus-systems.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.0/index.html#user-guide/autoscaling_examples_intro.html]

*Set up a AutoScaling  and Load-Balanced Application* (modified version of http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/as-register-lbs-with-asg.html)

\[\*\]  _Prerequisites_ -  Elastic Load Balancer should already be created. Please refer to https://www-stage.eucalyptus-systems.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.0/index.html#user-guide/elb_examples_basic_config.html for additional infomration.  For this example, 'MyLoadBalancer' is the Elastic Load Balancer.

1) [Optional] Create Launch Configuration.  Skip this step if you want to use your own launch configuration.
{code}
$ euscale-create-launch-config MyLaunchConfig --image-id emi-50783D25 --instance-type m1.medium --group mysecuritygroup
{code}

2) Create an Auto Scaling group with a load balancer.
{code}
$ euscale-create-auto-scaling-group MyScalingGroup --launch-configuration MyLaunchConfig --load-balancers MyLoadBalancer --availability-zones AcmeAvailabilityZone --min-size 2 --max-size 4
{code}

3) Authorize Load Balancer for back-end port communication with AutoScaling security group based on launch configuration.
{code}
$ eulb-describe-lbs --show-long
LOAD_BALANCER	MyLoadBalancer	MyLoadBalancer-408396244283.elb.acme.eucalyptus-systems.com			{interval=200,target=HTTP:80/,timeout=3,healthy-threshold=2,unhealthy-threshold=4}		AcmeAvailabilityZone		{protocol=HTTP,lb-port=80,instance-protocol=HTTP,instance-port=80}					{owner-alias=944786667073,group-name=euca-internal-408396244283-MyLoadBalancer}		2014-05-28T18:13:17.902Z
$  euca-authorize mysecuritygroup -u 944786667073 -o euca-internal-408396244283-MyLoadBalancer -p -1
{code}

4) Verify that your Auto Scaling group has been created with a load balancer.
{code}
$ euscale-describe-auto-scaling-groups
AUTO-SCALING-GROUP	MyScalingGroup	MyLaunchConfig	AcmeAvailabilityZone	MyLoadBalancer	2	4	2	Default
INSTANCE	i-DFCD0CBC	AcmeAvailabilityZone	InService	Healthy	MyLaunchConfig
INSTANCE	i-B3431043	AcmeAvailabilityZone	InService	Healthy	MyLaunchConfig
{code}

Improvement - Using Auto Scaling / Auto Scaling Usage Examples / Configuring Health Checks - https://www-stage.eucalyptus-systems.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.0/index.html#user-guide/autoscaling_examples_health_checks.html

Currently, we mention the following:
{quote}
By default, Auto Scaling group determines the health state of each instance by periodically checking the results of instance status checks. You can specify using the ELB health check method in addition to using the instance health check method.
{quote}

This is somewhat vague because there aren't any examples of using an AutoScaling Group with a Load Balancer.   It would be helpful if we could update the AutoScaling Usage Examples to include the AutoScaling and Load Balanced Application mention above, and improve this information here.  Maybe updating it to say the following:
{quote}
By default, Auto Scaling group determines the health state of each instance by periodically checking the results of instance status checks. However, if you have associated an Autoscaling group with an Elastic Load Balancer, you can specify using the ELB health check method in addition to using the Instance health check method.
{quote}
